ENTRY            C3093   20251211   20260312   20260312       C253
SUBENT        C3093001   20251211   20260312   20260312       C253
BIB                 11         44
TITLE      Elastic scattering in the 12N+197Au system at Elab=70
           MeV
AUTHOR     (P.L.D.Magro,V.Guimaraes,R.Linares,J.Rangel,
           J.C.Zamora,G.V.Rogachev,E.Koshchiy,J.Bishop,M.Barbui,
           C.E.Parker,B.Roeder,A.Saastomoinen)
INSTITUTE  (3BZLUSP,3BZLUFR,1USAMSU,1USATAM,2UK BIR)
           (3BZLBZL) Departamento de Matematica, Fisica e
           Computacao, Universidade do Estado do Rio de Janeiro,
           Faculdade de Tecnologia, 27537-000 Resende,
           Rio de Janeiro, Brazil
REFERENCE  (J,PR/C,111,034609,2025)
           #doi:10.1103/PhysRevC.111.034609
FACILITY   (CYCLO,1USATAM) The K150 cyclotron accelerator at the
           Cyclotron Institute of Texas A&M University, Texas,
           USA.
INC-SPECT  The radioactive 12N beam was produced from the
           3He(10B,12N) n reaction. Due to the similarity in
           magnetic rigidity, the secondary beam was composed of
           12N7+(44%) and 7Be4+(56%) ions. The average rate
           of 12N during the experimental runs was about 10**3
           pps. The energies of the 12N and 7Be beams, after the
           scintillator detector and before hitting the 197Au
           target, were 73.3 MeV and 42.0 MeV, respectively.
DETECTOR   (SISD) The detection system consisted of three 500-
           microm-thick double-sided silicon strip detectors
            (DSSSD) with front and back sides segmented in 128
           strips.
SAMPLE     A 4.7-mg/cm2-thick 197Au film was mounted on a target
           holder set at ~30 degree relative to the secondary
           beam axis. The energy loss of the 12N through the
           197Au target is about 6.5 MeV.
METHOD     The produced 12N particles were selected by the
           momentum achromatic recoil spectrometer (MARS). The
           intensity of the beam was monitored by a scintillator
           detector positioned downstream of the MARS beam line.
           The elastically scattered 12N and 7Be particles are
           clearly distinguished in the energy spectra at forward
           angles. The yield of 7Be is very faint at backward
           angles due to the lower cross section compared to the
           yield of 12N.
CORRECTION Estimates from the Monte Carlo simulation were
           employed to correct the measured yields and obtain
           the elastic cross section.
HISTORY    (20251211C) BP
ENDBIB              44
COMMON               1          3
EN
MEV
       70.0
ENDCOMMON            3
ENDSUBENT           51
SUBENT        C3093002   20251211   20260312   20260312       C253
BIB                  4         22
REACTION   (79-AU-197(7-N-12,EL)79-AU-197,,DA,,RTH)
ANALYSIS   The angular resolution is estimated to be about 3
           degree (in the laboratory reference system), based on
           the size of the beam spot on the target, the relative
           distances between the target detectors, and the width
           of the strip of the DSSSD detectors. The yields for
           the 12N scattering particles were determined from the
           fit of a Gaussian curve on the peak in the energy
           spectra, whenever the counting was statistically
           significant, and by integration of the region for the
           elastic event, defined according to the energy
           resolution and centered on the elastic scattering
           energy. Although the energy resolution does not allow
           for the distinction of elastic from inelastic
           scattering, in this work authors use the term elastic
           cross section since the inelastic cross section is
           estimated to be negligible, according to
           coupled-channel calculations.
ERR-ANALYS (ERR-S) Statistical uncertainties.
           (ERR-SYS) Systematic uncertainties (beam axis and
           target thickness uniformity).
STATUS     (CURVE,,P.L.D.Magro+,J,PR/C,111,034609,2025) Fig. - 3
